50|$|Typically, {{water is}} {{supplied}} from some height above the instrument through a pipe, and air is {{introduced into the}} water stream by aspiration (using the Bernoulli effect) into the main pipe from a side-pipe holding its top above the water source. Both water and air arrive together in the camera aeolis (wind chamber). Here, water and air separate and the compressed air is driven into a <b>wind-trunk</b> {{on top of the}} camera aeolis, to blow the organ pipes. Two perforated ‘splash plates’ or ‘diaphragms’ prevent water spray from getting into the organ pipes.|$|E

